Bankruptcy of indebted countries

125
00:14:20,407 --> 00:14:24,798
<i>An alliance of foreign banks</i>
<i>and multinationals</i>

126
00:14:24,967 --> 00:14:27,925
<i>comes to power in Argentina.</i>

127
00:14:28,567 --> 00:14:31,479
<i>After 7 years</i>
<i>of neo-liberal policies,</i>

128
00:14:31,767 --> 00:14:36,966
<i>the dictatorship leaves a country</i>
<i>bled dry, with a foreign debt</i>

129
00:14:37,167 --> 00:14:40,159
<i>of 45 billion dollars,</i>

130
00:14:40,767 --> 00:14:43,759
<i>of which half</i>
<i>is a private debt.</i>

131
00:14:46,567 --> 00:14:48,922
<i>23 billion</i>

132
00:14:49,087 --> 00:14:53,285
<i>is owed by multinationals</i>
<i>operating in the country</i>

133
00:14:53,887 --> 00:14:56,242
<i>like Citibank, First Boston,</i>

134
00:14:56,407 --> 00:15:00,798
<i>Chase Manhattan,</i>
<i>Bank of America, Banco de Italia,</i>

135
00:15:00,967 --> 00:15:05,085
<i>Banco de Londres, Banco Español,</i>
<i>Banco Francés, Deutsche Bank,</i>

136
00:15:05,247 --> 00:15:08,205
<i>Banco Río and Banco Quilmes,</i>

137
00:15:08,367 --> 00:15:10,358
<i>Banco Galicia and many more.</i>

138
00:15:10,847 --> 00:15:14,601
<i>And by multinationals</i>
<i>like Esso, Fiat, IBM,</i>

139
00:15:14,767 --> 00:15:18,919
<i>Ford, Mercedes Benz, Swift, Pirelli,</i>

140
00:15:19,087 --> 00:15:24,366
<i>as well as local groups owned by</i>
<i>Pérez Companc, Bulgheroni-Bridas,</i>

141
00:15:24,527 --> 00:15:27,439
<i>Macri, Techint, Fortabat,</i>

142
00:15:27,607 --> 00:15:31,122
<i>Pescarmona, Gruneisen, Soldati,</i>

143
00:15:31,327 --> 00:15:34,285
<i>Cogasco, Celulosa and others.</i>

144
00:15:35,007 --> 00:15:37,521
<i>An excessive private debt</i>

145
00:15:37,687 --> 00:15:42,078
<i>that a top bureaucrat of the</i>
<i>dictatorship saddled the State with:</i>

146
00:15:42,247 --> 00:15:44,078
<i>Domingo Cavallo.</i>

147
00:15:49,167 --> 00:15:54,400
<i>A "super-Minister" of Finance in the</i>
<i>Menem and De la Rúa governments,</i>

148
00:15:54,727 --> 00:15:59,243
<i>he is responsible</i>
<i>of the unending growth of the debt</i>

149
00:15:59,407 --> 00:16:03,719
<i>and the worst pillage ever suffered</i>
<i>by the Argentinean people.</i>

150
00:16:09,487 --> 00:16:11,443
<i>THIEVES, BANKERS, GOVERNMENTS</i>

151
00:16:11,647 --> 00:16:14,400
<i>GIVE US BACK OUR DOLLARS</i>

152
00:16:17,007 --> 00:16:18,520
What did you say?

153
00:16:19,287 --> 00:16:21,721
The police protects the thieves,
Mr. Solanas.

154
00:16:21,887 --> 00:16:23,684
The world's turned upside-down.

155
00:16:24,287 --> 00:16:28,041
Now people must
demonstrate peacefully

156
00:16:28,207 --> 00:16:31,916
to defend their savings,
that were confiscated by the banks

157
00:16:32,087 --> 00:16:34,317
with government complicity.

158
00:16:34,767 --> 00:16:37,725
The State
should guarantee citizens' rights,

159
00:16:37,887 --> 00:16:39,605
not steal them.

160
00:16:46,607 --> 00:16:48,643
Thieves!

161
00:16:50,687 --> 00:16:53,360
A dollar at a time,

162
00:16:53,527 --> 00:16:57,440
I saved during
the 25 years I worked,

163
00:16:57,607 --> 00:17:01,077
so I could live decently
when I retired,

164
00:17:01,247 --> 00:17:02,839
not on a State pension.

165
00:17:03,127 --> 00:17:05,163
Why don't the banks
treat us

166
00:17:05,327 --> 00:17:07,841
like their foreign customers?

167
00:17:08,167 --> 00:17:11,955
I chose private banks,
I didn't trust ours.

168
00:17:12,127 --> 00:17:14,960
I already got swindled in 1989.

169
00:17:15,127 --> 00:17:17,118
But I must be stupid.

170
00:17:17,527 --> 00:17:21,076
What do they want? A bomb?
That's not my style,

171
00:17:21,327 --> 00:17:23,602
that's why
I'm banging on my pan.

172
00:17:23,767 --> 00:17:25,837
I used to cook with it
for my kids.

173
00:17:26,247 --> 00:17:31,002
Every time I look at it,
I'll be reminded of those scoundrels,

174
00:17:31,167 --> 00:17:32,839
but I'll know I fought
for my rights.

175
00:17:33,367 --> 00:17:36,279
I'm the oldest newsvendor
in Avellaneda.

176
00:17:36,447 --> 00:17:39,007
For 65 years I've sold newspapers.

177
00:17:39,167 --> 00:17:41,727
All my savings
are in Citibank.

178
00:17:41,887 --> 00:17:45,277
The manager of the agency
says they'll return them to me,

179
00:17:45,447 --> 00:17:47,199
it's a lie!

180
00:17:47,727 --> 00:17:51,879
Everything I saved by making
sacrifices is in their hands.

181
00:17:53,647 --> 00:17:55,205
In fact, the foreign banks

182
00:17:55,367 --> 00:17:58,279
owe money to the Argentineans.

183
00:17:58,567 --> 00:18:01,365
In a way,
it's a reversed debt.

184
00:18:01,527 --> 00:18:05,361
The parent companies must be
responsible for the deposits.

185
00:18:05,887 --> 00:18:09,846
That was decided by law
in Argentina in 1971,

186
00:18:10,087 --> 00:18:12,123
in the well-known Swift Deltec case,

187
00:18:12,287 --> 00:18:16,838
which established that
parent companies were responsible

188
00:18:17,367 --> 00:18:19,801
for the debts of their subsidiaries.

189
00:18:19,967 --> 00:18:23,926
It's a swindle
to make the government responsible

190
00:18:24,087 --> 00:18:26,282
for the debts of the banks.

191
00:18:26,647 --> 00:18:28,478
What about our foreign debt?

192
00:18:28,647 --> 00:18:31,445
In many ways,
that debt is illegitimate.

193
00:18:31,607 --> 00:18:33,802
In a fundamental way:

194
00:18:33,967 --> 00:18:37,164
It's illegitimate
to repay the banks

195
00:18:37,327 --> 00:18:39,636
with 18 million people
poverty-stricken

196
00:18:39,807 --> 00:18:41,763
and 9 million paupers.

197
00:18:41,927 --> 00:18:43,804
There's a human priority.

198
00:18:44,687 --> 00:18:48,726
Then the banks
charged usurious interest rates.

199
00:18:48,887 --> 00:18:55,156
If they'd charged
normal interest rates,

200
00:18:55,327 --> 00:18:59,400
the foreign debt
would have been paid off by 1988.

201
00:18:59,647 --> 00:19:01,000
What was this swindle?

202
00:19:01,167 --> 00:19:04,284
The parent companies
made loans to their subsidiaries,

203
00:19:04,447 --> 00:19:06,961
so these were internal movements.

204
00:19:07,287 --> 00:19:10,757
These loans
were assigned to the foreign debt,

205
00:19:10,927 --> 00:19:13,885
when in fact
they were internal to the companies.

206
00:19:14,207 --> 00:19:19,201
Dollars were bought here, and placed
in accounts in the United States.

207
00:19:19,367 --> 00:19:22,803
With this deposit as collateral,
you got a loan

208
00:19:22,967 --> 00:19:25,959
to purchase more dollars
and so on,

209
00:19:26,127 --> 00:19:28,687
because of the difference
in interest rates.

210
00:19:29,007 --> 00:19:32,317
It's what's known
as "bicycling" funds,

211
00:19:32,487 --> 00:19:33,920
and many got rich on it.

212
00:19:34,087 --> 00:19:37,762
The main beneficiaries
were the big conglomerates,

213
00:19:37,927 --> 00:19:39,883
as usual.

214
00:19:41,287 --> 00:19:43,926
<i>At the end</i>
<i>of Alfonsín's presidency,</i>

215
00:19:44,087 --> 00:19:48,797
<i>the foreign debt</i>
<i>was close to 54 billion dollars.</i>

216
00:19:49,447 --> 00:19:54,999
<i>Menem let the creditors</i>
<i>determine what they were owed.</i>

217
00:19:55,247 --> 00:19:57,556
<i>The Congress</i>
<i>never debated on the debt,</i>

218
00:19:57,727 --> 00:19:59,718
<i>neglecting the Constitution</i>

219
00:19:59,887 --> 00:20:02,606
<i>and a decision by the law courts.</i>

220
00:20:02,767 --> 00:20:04,359
<i>Ten years later,</i>

221
00:20:04,527 --> 00:20:08,042
<i>the debt reached</i>
<i>130 billion dollars.</i>

222
00:20:08,447 --> 00:20:12,486
<i>People have a false idea</i>
<i>of the debt.</i>

223
00:20:12,687 --> 00:20:13,915
<i>You get into debt,</i>

224
00:20:14,087 --> 00:20:16,123
<i>then you say it's bad.</i>

225
00:20:16,967 --> 00:20:19,276
<i>But indebtedness</i>
<i>is what enables credit.</i>

226
00:20:19,567 --> 00:20:21,762
<i>Indebtedness is beneficial.</i>

227
00:20:21,927 --> 00:20:25,602
<i>We are going to develop credit</i>
<i>for everyone...</i>

228
00:20:25,767 --> 00:20:27,837
<i>Owing money is fine.</i>

229
00:20:29,967 --> 00:20:32,481
A good example

230
00:20:32,807 --> 00:20:37,403
is what the North Americans
invented around 1898,

231
00:20:37,567 --> 00:20:40,001
at the time they occupied Cuba.

232
00:20:40,167 --> 00:20:41,964
Some Spanish banks

233
00:20:42,127 --> 00:20:45,437
had granted loans
to the colonial government of Cuba.

234
00:20:45,607 --> 00:20:47,245
The North Americans said:

235
00:20:47,407 --> 00:20:53,676
If the Cuban people
didn't benefit from these loans,

236
00:20:53,847 --> 00:20:55,519
there's no public debt.

237
00:20:55,727 --> 00:20:57,718
In 1923,

238
00:20:58,527 --> 00:21:01,200
a British bank,

239
00:21:01,367 --> 00:21:03,483
the Royal Bank of Canada,

240
00:21:03,927 --> 00:21:07,681
lent a petty tyrant of Costa Rica,

241
00:21:07,847 --> 00:21:09,485
called Tinoco,

242
00:21:09,647 --> 00:21:13,686
a sum that he used
for personal goals.

243
00:21:13,847 --> 00:21:17,920
The Royal Bank of Canada
asked Costa Rica for repayment.

244
00:21:18,087 --> 00:21:20,203
There was a lawsuit,

245
00:21:20,367 --> 00:21:24,360
of which the arbitrator was
an ex-president of the United States,

246
00:21:24,527 --> 00:21:26,483
President William Taft.

247
00:21:26,647 --> 00:21:29,957
President Taft
ruled in the litigation, saying:

248
00:21:30,167 --> 00:21:32,442
It's about a private debt,

249
00:21:32,607 --> 00:21:34,962
not a public debt.

250
00:21:35,127 --> 00:21:39,120
You can't have
a public debt without a "public",

251
00:21:39,287 --> 00:21:42,916
with the public
as the beneficiary of the debt.

252
00:21:43,607 --> 00:21:47,441
These operations
never benefited the public,

253
00:21:47,607 --> 00:21:49,245
quite the contrary.

254
00:21:49,407 --> 00:21:54,322
It's the person
who shops in a supermarket

255
00:21:54,487 --> 00:21:57,047
and pays VAT

256
00:21:57,207 --> 00:21:59,596
who ends up paying

257
00:21:59,767 --> 00:22:03,965
for the private debts
of big enterprises,

258
00:22:04,127 --> 00:22:05,765
or of very rich people.

259
00:22:06,367 --> 00:22:09,279
The problem of private debts,

260
00:22:10,327 --> 00:22:14,286
that were illicitly nationalized

261
00:22:15,367 --> 00:22:16,800
by Mr. Cavallo,

262
00:22:16,967 --> 00:22:19,765
must absolutely be reexamined.

263
00:22:19,927 --> 00:22:21,201
What is this theory?

264
00:22:21,367 --> 00:22:24,040
It's the theory
of the Odious Debt.

265
00:22:24,567 --> 00:22:28,765
A director of the IMF,
Karen Lissakers,

266
00:22:28,927 --> 00:22:31,487
representing the United States,
said:

267
00:22:31,647 --> 00:22:35,799
"If we applied
the theory of the Odious Debt,

268
00:22:36,047 --> 00:22:39,562
"the Third World's debt
would no longer exist."

269
00:22:42,927 --> 00:22:46,715
A CHRONICLE OF TREASON

270
00:22:50,567 --> 00:22:52,046
<i>Democracy was re-established</i>

271
00:22:52,207 --> 00:22:55,199
<i>with the Radical Raúl Alfonsín</i>

272
00:22:55,607 --> 00:22:58,485
<i>and his social-democrat approach.</i>

273
00:22:59,607 --> 00:23:01,962
<i>He promised</i>
<i>to defend human rights,</i>

274
00:23:02,127 --> 00:23:04,561
<i>to fight poverty</i>

275
00:23:04,727 --> 00:23:09,926
<i>and to show that in a democracy</i>
<i>"you get education, care, and food".</i>

276
00:23:14,087 --> 00:23:17,523
<i>We have the huge responsibility</i>

277
00:23:18,767 --> 00:23:21,201
<i>of guaranteeing democracy</i>

278
00:23:21,367 --> 00:23:25,883
<i>and respect for human dignity</i>
<i>in Argentina.</i>

279
00:23:29,007 --> 00:23:30,122
<i>As we've said,</i>

280
00:23:30,407 --> 00:23:32,841
<i>this means that the State</i>

281
00:23:33,047 --> 00:23:36,801
<i>cannot bow</i>
<i>to international financial groups,</i>

282
00:23:37,687 --> 00:23:41,919
<i>or to privileged local groups...</i>

283
00:23:42,087 --> 00:23:43,839
<i>But the State was bankrupt,</i>

284
00:23:44,087 --> 00:23:45,839
<i>and had to make a choice.</i>

285
00:23:48,567 --> 00:23:51,365
<i>Economy minister Grinspun,</i>
<i>suggested repudiating the debt</i>

286
00:23:51,527 --> 00:23:54,246
<i>and favoring growth.</i>

287
00:23:54,447 --> 00:23:58,645
<i>Alfonsín won't go along,</i>
<i>and yields to financial power.</i>

288
00:23:58,927 --> 00:24:02,476
<i>The only solution</i>
<i>is a policy of austerity,</i>

289
00:24:02,687 --> 00:24:04,598
<i>that will be very hard</i>

290
00:24:04,767 --> 00:24:07,361
<i>and require great efforts</i>
<i>by everyone.</i>

291
00:24:07,887 --> 00:24:11,436
<i>It's called,</i>
<i>my dear compatriots,</i>

292
00:24:11,927 --> 00:24:14,202
<i>an economy of war.</i>

293
00:24:14,367 --> 00:24:17,996
<i>We must all learn from it.</i>

294
00:24:21,607 --> 00:24:25,202
<i>This drastic measure</i>
<i>is called "Plan Austral".</i>

295
00:24:25,527 --> 00:24:26,801
<i>Once more,</i>

296
00:24:26,967 --> 00:24:29,162
<i>huge public funds</i>

297
00:24:29,327 --> 00:24:32,285
<i>are transferred to the banks</i>
<i>and big corporations.</i>

298
00:24:33,247 --> 00:24:36,125
<i>Alfonsín says two things at once:</i>

299
00:24:36,447 --> 00:24:38,199
<i>He promises to repudiate the debt</i>

300
00:24:38,407 --> 00:24:43,117
<i>but orders the president</i>
<i>of the Central Bank to legitimize it.</i>

301
00:24:45,927 --> 00:24:48,395
<i>He favors prosecuting Army officers</i>

302
00:24:48,567 --> 00:24:50,797
<i>for their crimes</i>
<i>during the dictatorship,</i>

303
00:24:51,327 --> 00:24:53,283
<i>but two years later,</i>

304
00:24:53,727 --> 00:24:57,242
<i>the "Due Obedience" laws</i>
<i>exonerate crimes committed</i>

305
00:24:57,447 --> 00:24:59,005
<i>on orders of a superior.</i>

306
00:25:01,847 --> 00:25:04,236
<i>Laws that resulted</i>
<i>from the insurrection</i>

307
00:25:04,407 --> 00:25:07,444
<i>of the rebel</i>
<i>"painted face" officers.</i>

308
00:25:08,847 --> 00:25:11,042
<i>People took to the streets</i>

309
00:25:11,207 --> 00:25:13,243
<i>and defied the tanks...</i>

310
00:25:13,807 --> 00:25:16,765
<i>We've had enough of jackboots!</i>

311
00:25:20,127 --> 00:25:23,358
<i>Alfonsín amnesties the rebels.</i>

312
00:25:23,527 --> 00:25:25,438
<i>Dear compatriots,</i>

313
00:25:26,727 --> 00:25:28,718
<i>Happy Easter!</i>

314
00:25:31,327 --> 00:25:34,080
<i>The insurgents...</i>

315
00:25:35,407 --> 00:25:38,285
<i>have put down their weapons.</i>

316
00:25:40,567 --> 00:25:42,364
<i>Among them,</i>

317
00:25:42,967 --> 00:25:46,243
<i>were heroes of the Falklands war,</i>

318
00:25:47,087 --> 00:25:49,555
<i>who had strayed...</i>

319
00:25:53,127 --> 00:25:55,322
<i>The electoral defeat</i>
<i>of the Radical party</i>

320
00:25:55,807 --> 00:25:57,843
<i>accelerates the crisis.</i>

321
00:25:58,527 --> 00:26:02,042
<i>Stockmarket instability</i>
<i>and hyperinflation</i>

322
00:26:02,207 --> 00:26:05,119
<i>lead to runs on the supermarkets.</i>

323
00:26:06,167 --> 00:26:08,237
<i>I've decided to resign</i>

324
00:26:08,727 --> 00:26:11,719
<i>from the job</i>
<i>of President of Argentina...</i>

325
00:26:14,727 --> 00:26:16,558
<i>Alfonsín has to resign</i>

326
00:26:16,727 --> 00:26:20,117
<i>6 months before the end</i>
<i>of his mandate.</i>

327
00:26:34,047 --> 00:26:36,242
<i>The neo-Peronist Carlos Menem</i>

328
00:26:36,887 --> 00:26:38,718
<i>becomes President</i>

329
00:26:38,887 --> 00:26:41,401
<i>after having,</i>
<i>for many years, governed</i>

330
00:26:41,567 --> 00:26:43,842
<i>the province of La Rioja,</i>

331
00:26:44,047 --> 00:26:46,242
<i>one of the poorest in the nation.</i>

332
00:26:49,447 --> 00:26:51,165
<i>His lightning rise</i>

333
00:26:51,567 --> 00:26:54,604
<i>coincided</i>
<i>with the fall of the Berlin wall</i>

334
00:26:54,767 --> 00:26:57,520
<i>and the ideas</i>
<i>of the "Consensus of Washington".</i>

335
00:27:00,007 --> 00:27:03,283
<i>With his frankness</i>
<i>and his preacher's gestures,</i>

336
00:27:03,567 --> 00:27:07,276
<i>he promises a Productivist Revolution</i>
<i>and big wages.</i>

337
00:27:10,727 --> 00:27:15,198
<i>He has long sideburns</i>
<i>like the old rebel Facundo Quiroga,</i>

338
00:27:15,527 --> 00:27:17,836
<i>the "Tiger of the Plains".</i>

339
00:27:23,127 --> 00:27:25,641
<i>For every Argentinean, standing,</i>

340
00:27:26,047 --> 00:27:28,641
<i>for poor children who are hungry,</i>

341
00:27:28,807 --> 00:27:31,480
<i>or who are sad,</i>

342
00:27:31,647 --> 00:27:33,956
<i>for our brothers without work,</i>

343
00:27:34,127 --> 00:27:36,402
<i>for the homes without a roof,</i>

344
00:27:36,647 --> 00:27:38,877
<i>for the tables without bread,</i>

345
00:27:39,047 --> 00:27:40,765
<i>for our homeland,</i>

346
00:27:40,927 --> 00:27:43,805
<i>I ask you to follow me,</i>

347
00:27:44,087 --> 00:27:45,440
<i>follow me,</i>

348
00:27:45,607 --> 00:27:47,677
<i>I won't betray you,</i>

349
00:27:47,847 --> 00:27:49,963
<i>I won't betray you...</i>

350
00:27:52,207 --> 00:27:54,437
<i>As God is my witness,</i>

351
00:27:55,207 --> 00:27:57,357
<i>and facing</i>
<i>the judgment of History,</i>

352
00:27:57,887 --> 00:27:59,957
<i>let me proclaim:</i>

353
00:28:00,367 --> 00:28:04,326
<i>Argentina, get up and walk!</i>

354
00:28:04,767 --> 00:28:06,644
<i>Sisters and brothers,</i>

355
00:28:07,207 --> 00:28:10,517
<i>in a single voice</i>
<i>I say to the world:</i>

356
00:28:11,047 --> 00:28:13,607
<i>"This is the advent</i>

357
00:28:14,167 --> 00:28:16,362
<i>of a new and glorious Nation."</i>

358
00:28:20,927 --> 00:28:25,000
<i>This is the era of the theory</i>
<i>of the "End of History",</i>

359
00:28:26,207 --> 00:28:29,756
<i>of the single-mindedness</i>
<i>of globalization</i>

360
00:28:30,127 --> 00:28:34,359
<i>and of neo-liberal democracies</i>
<i>in Latin America.</i>

361
00:28:36,807 --> 00:28:39,082
Long live Carlos Saúl Menem!

362
00:28:43,007 --> 00:28:44,440
<i>A few days later,</i>

363
00:28:44,607 --> 00:28:48,441
<i>he abandons his sideburns</i>
<i>and his promised reforms,</i>

364
00:28:48,607 --> 00:28:51,075
<i>and betrays his voters:</i>

365
00:28:51,927 --> 00:28:56,557
<i>His program becomes that</i>
<i>of the liberal conservative minority,</i>

366
00:28:57,287 --> 00:29:00,836
<i>directed by the former rebel officer</i>
<i>Alvaro Alsogaray.</i>

367
00:29:01,207 --> 00:29:04,483
<i>Everything has changed now,</i>
<i>there's a new relationship</i>

368
00:29:05,087 --> 00:29:07,362
<i>between conservatives</i>
<i>and Peronists.</i>

369
00:29:07,927 --> 00:29:10,316
<i>We appear to be the same,</i>

370
00:29:10,487 --> 00:29:12,717
<i>but a fundamental change</i>

371
00:29:12,927 --> 00:29:14,918
<i>amongst us has occurred.</i>

372
00:29:15,087 --> 00:29:17,647
<i>Historically, it's only fair,</i>

373
00:29:17,807 --> 00:29:21,083
<i>that a neo-Peronist president</i>
<i>should bring this about...</i>

374
00:29:23,847 --> 00:29:25,917
<i>No one before Menem</i>

375
00:29:26,087 --> 00:29:29,238
<i>had dared to carry treason so far,</i>

376
00:29:29,607 --> 00:29:31,996
<i>or undertaken so cynically</i>

377
00:29:32,567 --> 00:29:35,127
<i>actions that harmed the Nation.</i>

378
00:29:36,567 --> 00:29:38,319
<i>The two-faced game</i>
<i>of the new leader</i>

379
00:29:39,247 --> 00:29:43,479
<i>will pulverize 50 years</i>
<i>of popular resistance:</i>

380
00:29:44,207 --> 00:29:48,246
<i>He imposes allegiance</i>
<i>to the global model,</i>

381
00:29:48,407 --> 00:29:50,682
<i>amnesties the leaders of the junta,</i>

382
00:29:50,847 --> 00:29:53,122
<i>and betrays millions of workers</i>

383
00:29:53,487 --> 00:29:55,682
<i>who lived through the repression.</i>

384
00:29:58,007 --> 00:30:00,475
<i>He abandons</i>
<i>popular anti-imperialism</i>

385
00:30:00,647 --> 00:30:04,162
<i>and non-alignment</i>
<i>extolled by Perôn and Evita</i>

386
00:30:04,327 --> 00:30:08,161
<i>and initiates a "physical relationship"</i>
<i>with the United States.</i>

387
00:30:09,727 --> 00:30:14,198
<i>His policies will be dictated</i>
<i>by the World Bank and the IMF.</i>

388
00:30:21,447 --> 00:30:24,803
<i>But Menem</i>
<i>is not the only one who betrayed.</i>

389
00:30:25,607 --> 00:30:28,360
<i>Many of the political</i>
<i>and union leaders</i>

390
00:30:29,327 --> 00:30:32,876
<i>dumped overboard</i>
<i>a whole life of resistance.</i>

391
00:30:33,207 --> 00:30:35,880
<i>Many of them</i>
<i>accepted arrangements</i>

392
00:30:36,047 --> 00:30:38,038
<i>and opted for indemnifications.</i>

393
00:30:39,887 --> 00:30:41,479
<i>Others climbed</i>

394
00:30:42,007 --> 00:30:46,364
<i>onto the bandwagon</i>
<i>of privatizations.</i>

395
00:31:03,127 --> 00:31:04,560
Senator Cafiero,

396
00:31:04,727 --> 00:31:07,878
you are a historic leader
of the Peronist party.

397
00:31:08,047 --> 00:31:10,197
How do you explain
Menem's treason?

398
00:31:10,807 --> 00:31:14,117
It happens frequently

399
00:31:14,287 --> 00:31:18,200
in the political life
of every nation.

400
00:31:18,367 --> 00:31:22,838
There's a small French book,
"In Praise of Treason",

401
00:31:23,087 --> 00:31:25,726
where they prove

402
00:31:26,007 --> 00:31:28,999
that treason
is part and parcel of politics.

403
00:31:29,167 --> 00:31:32,000
To succeed, you have to lie.

404
00:31:32,167 --> 00:31:36,240
If you say what you think,
no one will vote for you.

405
00:31:36,407 --> 00:31:39,046
That's what happened
in Argentina,

406
00:31:39,207 --> 00:31:42,324
but much more intensely,
let's face it,

407
00:31:42,487 --> 00:31:44,318
when Menem was in power.

408
00:31:44,487 --> 00:31:48,719
He even admitted
he hid his goals to get elected.

409
00:31:49,127 --> 00:31:52,085
Of course, in my opinion,

410
00:31:52,727 --> 00:31:55,366
it's politically unethical,

411
00:31:55,527 --> 00:31:57,404
but that's the reality.

412
00:31:57,567 --> 00:32:01,480
Then, some international
parameters changed...

413
00:32:02,967 --> 00:32:05,606
And the model gradually
exhausted itself.

414
00:32:06,407 --> 00:32:08,398
How do you explain

415
00:32:08,767 --> 00:32:11,042
the existence
of a real "mafiocracy"?

416
00:32:12,007 --> 00:32:15,795
Economic power,
banks and the political class...

417
00:32:15,967 --> 00:32:17,685
On that, Pino,

418
00:32:19,927 --> 00:32:22,077
I won't pass judgment...

419
00:32:23,607 --> 00:32:26,917
how can I put it...
in an absolute way.

420
00:32:27,447 --> 00:32:29,961
My long experience

421
00:32:30,127 --> 00:32:32,721
has taught me
that things are relative.

422
00:32:32,887 --> 00:32:34,525
It's not all black or white,

423
00:32:34,687 --> 00:32:36,757
things aren't corrupt or pure.

424
00:32:36,927 --> 00:32:40,078
Argentinean society as a whole

425
00:32:40,247 --> 00:32:42,044
can't call itself pure

426
00:32:42,207 --> 00:32:45,244
and assign corruption
to the ruling classes.

427
00:32:45,407 --> 00:32:49,161
The ruling classes
come from that society.

428
00:32:49,367 --> 00:32:51,927
On one hand,
we politicians have been a failure,

429
00:32:52,087 --> 00:32:54,317
and I'll assume
my part of responsibility.

430
00:32:55,767 --> 00:32:57,598
But on the other hand...

431
00:32:58,327 --> 00:33:01,717
many of the ruling circles
let us down,

432
00:33:01,887 --> 00:33:04,879
and to reach a verdict on everyone,

433
00:33:05,047 --> 00:33:07,686
I'd say we're all in Dante's hell.

434
00:33:09,927 --> 00:33:11,883
Undoubtedly,

435
00:33:12,767 --> 00:33:15,042
treason is very effective.

436
00:33:18,327 --> 00:33:23,242
Treason
has phenomenal political power,

437
00:33:23,687 --> 00:33:26,076
precisely because it's treason.

438
00:33:27,367 --> 00:33:29,403
It's insidious,

439
00:33:29,567 --> 00:33:33,082
it sneaks up behind you,
without warning,

440
00:33:33,247 --> 00:33:35,477
where you least expect it.

441
00:33:35,647 --> 00:33:38,115
Otherwise it wouldn't be treason.

442
00:33:39,327 --> 00:33:42,285
In this sense,
the neo-Peronist party

443
00:33:43,727 --> 00:33:49,165
was the most brilliant
representative

444
00:33:49,327 --> 00:33:51,318
of Cafiero's point of view.

445
00:33:52,167 --> 00:33:56,160
If you ask Argentinean society
to choose

446
00:33:56,327 --> 00:33:59,160
between San Martín
- our national hero - and Spiderman,

447
00:33:59,327 --> 00:34:01,318
it'll vote for San Martín.

448
00:34:01,487 --> 00:34:04,479
But between
Spiderman and Superman,

449
00:34:04,647 --> 00:34:08,959
how can you fault society
for the consequences of that choice?

450
00:34:09,447 --> 00:34:10,766
So we have...

451
00:34:11,527 --> 00:34:13,722
a society with a weakened role,

452
00:34:14,247 --> 00:34:18,763
a party that betrays its historic ideas
and surrenders to the enemy,

453
00:34:18,927 --> 00:34:23,762
a working-class movement
eroded by de-industrialization,

454
00:34:23,927 --> 00:34:25,758
infested with traitors...

455
00:34:26,367 --> 00:34:31,361
Law courts
that pay lip-service to all that,

456
00:34:31,527 --> 00:34:35,236
Opposition parties
without much room to maneuver...

457
00:34:35,407 --> 00:34:37,045
and the result of it all is...

458
00:34:37,687 --> 00:34:41,805
THE REPUBLIC DETERIORATES

459
00:34:54,047 --> 00:34:56,277
<i>Menem's neo-liberal model</i>

460
00:34:56,727 --> 00:35:01,562
<i>is inseparable from the deterioration</i>
<i>of the republic and corruption.</i>

461
00:35:03,727 --> 00:35:07,959
<i>His political plan</i>
<i>needs a biased Supreme Court</i>

462
00:35:08,127 --> 00:35:10,766
<i>and federal law courts</i>
<i>under his control,</i>

